  %li
    LabVIEW 2015 - Though it maybe didn’t have tons of pizazz, there are a few key features that I
    am definitely looking forward to. For more information you can check out the full list of
    #{ext_link 'LabVIEW 2015 features and changes', 'http://zone.ni.com/reference/en-XX/help/371361M-01/lvupgrade/labview_features/'},
    many of which originated on the
    #{ext_link 'idea exchange', 'http://forums.ni.com/ni/?category.id=ideas'}.
    %ol
      %li
        LabVIEW 2015 has a revamped “add space to block diagram” feature. Ctl+Mouse Drag
        still adds space to the block diagram, but the cool part is that they made it much easier
        to add space in just one direction. And then, even cooler, Ctl+Alt+Mouse Drag removes
        space from the block diagram!
      %li
        They have opened up the right click menus! Darren Nattinger and Stephen Loftus-
        Mercer did a great presentation on
        #{ext_link 'augmenting the right-click menus', 'https://decibel.ni.com/content/docs/DOC-43394'}.
        Essentially, it is  not super user-friendly to update them since there are different right-click menus all
        over LabVIEW based on where you are at in the program and what is being right-clicked
        on, but it can be done! I am most excited to rearrange the menus to put some of the
        right-click functionality that I constantly use closer to the top.
      %li
        Arrays in probes can now be resized! Yay! That was definitely a pain-point every once in
        a while that just made me cringe.
      %li
        Changing from an element to an array and back through the right-click menu will
        definitely be useful.
      %li
        Adding Hyperlinks to notes may turn out to be very helpful for documentation.
%p Happy Coding!!!
